00:40:53.340 --> 00:40:54.590
whose name I forget right now.

00:40:54.590 --> 00:40:59.149
He runs the NPR fund drive every
year, every quarter-- sorry.

00:40:59.149 --> 00:41:01.190
And we started talking,
and he said why don't you

00:41:01.190 --> 00:41:02.356
contribute a bunch of books?

00:41:02.356 --> 00:41:04.300
We'll talk about
your book on NPR.

00:41:04.300 --> 00:41:06.040
And I'm like, sure.

00:41:06.040 --> 00:41:08.454
So that happened.

00:41:08.454 --> 00:41:10.870
I actually went to a bunch of
local bookstores and I sold.

00:41:10.870 --> 00:41:13.830
I went to a bunch of
cafes, and actually my book

00:41:13.830 --> 00:41:18.890
is selling in 10 countries or
something like that, in cafes.

00:41:18.890 --> 00:41:22.020
So that was just one-on-one,
so this doesn't scale.

00:41:22.020 --> 00:41:25.610
Mostly to people who-- cafes
owned by people I wrote about,

00:41:25.610 --> 00:41:29.870
so they felt guilty
that they needed to buy.

00:41:29.870 --> 00:41:32.770
And for some reason
I got hot in Japan,

00:41:32.770 --> 00:41:39.160
because I wrote about one of
the most popular cafes there.

00:41:39.160 --> 00:41:44.670
And the owner used my book
as an English textbook.

00:41:44.670 --> 00:41:46.786
So people that used
to come to his shop

00:41:46.786 --> 00:41:48.910
would love to read my book
because they would learn

00:41:48.910 --> 00:41:50.785
about-- they were
interested in coffee anyway

00:41:50.785 --> 00:41:53.110
and they wanted to learn
English, so by reading my book

00:41:53.110 --> 00:41:56.614
they killed two birds
with one stone, literally.

00:41:56.614 --> 00:41:57.280
CHET HAASE: Huh.

00:41:57.280 --> 00:41:59.274
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:59.274 --> 00:42:00.690
ALON HALEVY: Things
that you never

00:42:00.690 --> 00:42:05.340
expect when you write a book.

00:42:05.340 --> 00:42:07.660
CHET HAASE: On my book,
it's basically word of mouth

00:42:07.660 --> 00:42:08.925
and it's social media.

00:42:08.925 --> 00:42:11.050
My social media outlets
are basically a whole bunch

00:42:11.050 --> 00:42:13.090
of followers on G+ and Twitter.

00:42:13.090 --> 00:42:14.550
But they're in a specific niche.

00:42:14.550 --> 00:42:16.091
They follow me
because they think I'm

00:42:16.091 --> 00:42:17.662
going to talk about Android.

00:42:17.662 --> 00:42:19.470
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:19.470 --> 00:42:21.680
ALON HALEVY: So they're
buying your book by mistake.

00:42:21.680 --> 00:42:24.287
CHET HAASE: Or not,
as it turns out.

00:42:24.287 --> 00:42:26.620
I keep hitting them with
comedy, and then eventually I'd

00:42:26.620 --> 00:42:28.300
say, by the way,
here's some books.

00:42:28.300 --> 00:42:29.680
Some of them buy it.

00:42:29.680 --> 00:42:32.510
But other than
that, word of mouth

00:42:32.510 --> 00:42:35.550
turns out not a real huge
way to market your books.

00:42:35.550 --> 00:42:38.029
I think you need to do things
like go to these conferences.

00:42:38.029 --> 00:42:39.320
You go and you give book talks.

00:42:39.320 --> 00:42:40.430
This is what real authors do.

00:42:40.430 --> 00:42:42.490
They go to bookstores,
they advertise this thing,

00:42:42.490 --> 00:42:43.277
they give a talk.

00:42:43.277 --> 00:42:45.110
It's a little bit harder
if your book is not

00:42:45.110 --> 00:42:46.660
about a particular thing.

00:42:46.660 --> 00:42:49.720
I think you have more luck if
you are trying to teach them

00:42:49.720 --> 00:42:52.557
about coffee, if you're trying
to have a particular experience

00:42:52.557 --> 00:42:54.640
that you're driving with
that, as opposed to, hey,

00:42:54.640 --> 00:42:56.260
here's some funny essays.

00:42:56.260 --> 00:42:57.968
ALON HALEVY: The other
thing, by the way,

00:42:57.968 --> 00:43:01.090
is give a talk about your book
two weeks before Christmas.

00:43:01.090 --> 00:43:05.180
That's what I did at Google
before when my book came out.

00:43:05.180 --> 00:43:05.680
So then--

00:43:05.680 --> 00:43:06.300
CHET HAASE: The gift thing.

00:43:06.300 --> 00:43:08.508
ALON HALEVY: --then the gift
thing works really well.

00:43:10.782 --> 00:43:13.240
CHET HAASE: So it turns out
that publishers I believe still

00:43:13.240 --> 00:43:15.531
offer a service, which is
actually marketing your book.

00:43:15.531 --> 00:43:17.430
Whether they do that
effectively or not,

00:43:17.430 --> 00:43:19.780
it's certainly part of the
business that they're in.

00:43:19.780 --> 00:43:23.700
So maybe that's something
that authors still

00:43:23.700 --> 00:43:25.200
take advantage of.

00:43:25.200 --> 00:43:27.910
OK, so why did we do this again?

00:43:27.910 --> 00:43:30.340
To me, publishing a
book is a great way

00:43:30.340 --> 00:43:31.300
of finishing a project.

00:43:31.300 --> 00:43:32.950
I really enjoy writing.

00:43:32.950 --> 00:43:37.180
What I found personally was that
I got much more into writing.

00:43:37.180 --> 00:43:40.780
I had thought about writing
more for about 20 years,

00:43:40.780 --> 00:43:43.360
and then when blogging
started, I actually

00:43:43.360 --> 00:43:46.300
started posting things
online, and that actually

00:43:46.300 --> 00:43:49.030
made me start writing instead
of talking about and thinking

00:43:49.030 --> 00:43:49.930
about writing.

00:43:49.930 --> 00:43:53.030
The idea that I could have
an idea, I could finish it,

00:43:53.030 --> 00:43:55.904
I could sort of craft it
in away with that I would

00:43:55.904 --> 00:43:57.070
like other people to see it.

00:43:57.070 --> 00:43:58.528
I was happy enough
with the results

00:43:58.528 --> 00:44:00.380
that I could have
other eyes on it

00:44:00.380 --> 00:44:04.090
was a great experience for me
actually doing more writing

00:44:04.090 --> 00:44:05.530
stuff that I was interested in.

00:44:05.530 --> 00:44:08.820
So I started publishing those
blogs in jokes and videos

00:44:08.820 --> 00:44:11.950
and whatever all
along, and then books

00:44:11.950 --> 00:44:14.610
are sort of the ultimate
version of that.

00:44:14.610 --> 00:44:16.110
It's a way of
finishing the project.

00:44:16.110 --> 00:44:18.640
It's a way of saying
I did all this stuff,

00:44:18.640 --> 00:44:21.530
and then I edited it, and
I crafted it into this form

00:44:21.530 --> 00:44:22.760
that I'm really proud of.

00:44:22.760 --> 00:44:24.700
Then you put it in a
book and you're done.

00:44:24.700 --> 00:44:26.890
And you can point to and
say, that's what I did.

00:44:26.890 --> 00:44:29.222
Maybe not a lot of
people know about it,

00:44:29.222 --> 00:44:31.430
but if they're curious about
it you can sort of point

00:44:31.430 --> 00:44:33.530
to this particular thing,
as opposed to saying,

00:44:33.530 --> 00:44:35.821
gee, I'd really like to write
some more about something

00:44:35.821 --> 00:44:36.550
someday.

00:44:36.550 --> 00:44:38.300
So to me it's about
finishing the project.

00:44:38.300 --> 00:44:40.970
It's about having this idea,
putting it all in somewhere

00:44:40.970 --> 00:44:45.180
and packaging it up and
actually finishing it.

00:44:45.180 --> 00:44:47.610
Turns out they're
also great gifts

00:44:47.610 --> 00:44:51.030
that you can give to people
that don't expect it.

00:44:51.030 --> 00:44:52.570
Did you get the same book twice?

00:44:52.570 --> 00:44:53.700
ALON HALEVY: I may have.

00:44:53.700 --> 00:44:54.550
I don't know.

00:44:56.689 --> 00:44:58.105
CHET HAASE: We
don't want to know.

00:44:58.105 --> 00:44:59.021
ALON HALEVY: Yeah, no.

00:44:59.021 --> 00:45:03.105
CHET HAASE: And it's the best
thing that Alon ever did,

00:45:03.105 --> 00:45:03.864
apparently.

00:45:03.864 --> 00:45:04.530
ALON HALEVY: No.

00:45:04.530 --> 00:45:06.760
It was a wonderful experience.

00:45:06.760 --> 00:45:09.730
It actually-- I don't know.

00:45:09.730 --> 00:45:11.840
A big part of my identity
is now tied to coffee.

00:45:11.840 --> 00:45:13.550
You can talk to people
in this room who

00:45:13.550 --> 00:45:16.590
have enjoyed having
a coffee guy around,

00:45:16.590 --> 00:45:20.620
or find it a bit
overwhelming, or too much.

00:45:20.620 --> 00:45:25.089
But yeah, no, it's been a
great exploration and project.

00:45:25.089 --> 00:45:26.880
CHET HAASE: Oh, I wanted
to point out, too,

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:28.890
the book that I've
been reading here.

00:45:28.890 --> 00:45:31.490
This as one weird thing
about print on demand

00:45:31.490 --> 00:45:35.910
is George ordered some
books, and one of them

00:45:35.910 --> 00:45:37.390
came in this bizarre format.

00:45:37.390 --> 00:45:39.410
The actual book
is about this big,

00:45:39.410 --> 00:45:43.440
and they cut this from a
different size piece of paper.

00:45:43.440 --> 00:45:44.640
It was the strangest thing.

00:45:44.640 --> 00:45:46.700
So a little
non-deterministic sometimes

00:45:46.700 --> 00:45:48.636
in how they print these things.

00:45:48.636 --> 00:45:50.760
ALON HALEVY: Yeah, see,
these are the random things

00:45:50.760 --> 00:45:53.010
that happen to you when you
write a book about coffee.

00:45:53.010 --> 00:45:55.410
So this is a coffee
farmer from Brazil sitting

00:45:55.410 --> 00:45:59.680
in a cafe in San Francisco
holding up my book,

00:45:59.680 --> 00:46:02.140
being tagged on
Facebook for doing that,

00:46:02.140 --> 00:46:04.570
and I had nothing
to do with this.

00:46:04.570 --> 00:46:06.324
It just-- and these
things happen.

00:46:06.324 --> 00:46:08.240
CHET HAASE: Random
stranger sucking up to you.

00:46:08.240 --> 00:46:10.489
ALON HALEVY: A random
stranger-- yeah, they're not-- I

00:46:10.489 --> 00:46:14.570
mean I don't know
what he's doing.

00:46:14.570 --> 00:46:18.840
CHET HAASE: This is right before
he winged it at the cameraman.

00:46:18.840 --> 00:46:21.970
So I wanted to end
on a serious note.

00:46:21.970 --> 00:46:26.016
"When there is a donut,
there's nothing wrong at all.

00:46:26.016 --> 00:46:27.640
Life could be ruined,
people could die,

00:46:27.640 --> 00:46:29.320
nations could crater and fall.

00:46:29.320 --> 00:46:31.925
But if there's a donut,
just one single donut,

00:46:31.925 --> 00:46:33.300
then everything's
good as can be.

00:46:33.300 --> 00:46:36.640
I open my mouth and suck it
all in an I am a happier me."

00:46:36.640 --> 00:46:38.740
"Some people might find
me vapid, my philosophy

00:46:38.740 --> 00:46:41.825
lacking and sad, but when I
taste the warm sugar and fat,

00:46:41.825 --> 00:46:43.805
I figure it can't be that bad."

00:46:43.805 --> 00:46:45.180
"Everyone has
their own weakness,

00:46:45.180 --> 00:46:47.010
their own special
things they adore.

00:46:47.010 --> 00:46:49.780
For some it's true love or power
or clothing or shopping all day

00:46:49.780 --> 00:46:50.970
at the store.

00:46:50.970 --> 00:46:52.970
For others it might be
fun gadgets or video

00:46:52.970 --> 00:46:54.800
games played all day long.

00:46:54.800 --> 00:46:56.570
And who am I to
judge these pursuits

00:46:56.570 --> 00:46:58.890
or tell everyone
that they're wrong?"

00:46:58.890 --> 00:47:00.470
But meanwhile, I
just need donuts.

00:47:00.470 --> 00:47:02.029
In fact, I'll just
have that one.

00:47:02.029 --> 00:47:04.070
And then when I'm done
with it I'll have another.

00:47:04.070 --> 00:47:05.764
This time a cinnamon bun."

00:47:05.764 --> 00:47:07.180
"So let all the
government's fail,

00:47:07.180 --> 00:47:09.550
and storms break the
Earth's crust apart.

00:47:09.550 --> 00:47:11.655
As long as I have
my one single donut,

00:47:11.655 --> 00:47:15.070
I'll also have joy in my heart."

00:47:15.070 --> 00:47:15.955
Thank you.

00:47:15.955 --> 00:47:21.780
[APPLAUSE]

00:47:21.780 --> 00:47:23.890
I don't know if
we have questions

00:47:23.890 --> 00:47:26.640
from this rather contentious
and controversial topic,

00:47:26.640 --> 00:47:28.487
but we're happy
to field them now.

