00:47:55.320 --> 00:47:56.660
AUDIENCE: Yeah, they do
enough to cover their costs,

00:47:56.660 --> 00:47:58.868
and they do enough to get
into some major bookstores.

00:47:58.868 --> 00:47:59.940
They do do that, yes.

00:47:59.940 --> 00:48:01.815
But basically, her books
have been a failure.

00:48:01.815 --> 00:48:02.910
You should buy them.

00:48:02.910 --> 00:48:05.260
CHET HAASE: And they do
at least the channels.

00:48:05.260 --> 00:48:09.380
Like part of the dynamic
that I figured out

00:48:09.380 --> 00:48:11.510
is, wow, to get
into these channels

00:48:11.510 --> 00:48:14.260
so that Barnes &amp; Nobles could
actually buy this thing,

00:48:14.260 --> 00:48:16.320
I need to charge this
much money, as opposed

00:48:16.320 --> 00:48:18.867
to like the publisher has the
scale where they can publish it

00:48:18.867 --> 00:48:20.950
at a lower cost and it'll
still be in the channel,

00:48:20.950 --> 00:48:23.760
and that is going to be pushed
to all of the people that

00:48:23.760 --> 00:48:25.140
buy from them.

00:48:25.140 --> 00:48:27.360
There's some amount of
just busy work stuff

00:48:27.360 --> 00:48:29.840
that they're doing beyond
the sheer marketing.

00:48:29.840 --> 00:48:32.970
But yeah, at the end of the
day, your friends on a $10 book

00:48:32.970 --> 00:48:35.299
might be making
$0.50 or something.

00:48:35.299 --> 00:48:36.340
Yeah, it's a little hard.

00:48:36.340 --> 00:48:38.160
I mean this is why my friend
in the publishing business

00:48:38.160 --> 00:48:39.740
was pushing me, like no, no, no.

00:48:39.740 --> 00:48:40.990
Do your own homework.

00:48:40.990 --> 00:48:42.160
You can totally do this.

00:48:42.160 --> 00:48:44.965
This is not something that
requires an advanced degree.

00:48:44.965 --> 00:48:46.840
You figure out when the
review deadlines are.

00:48:46.840 --> 00:48:48.240
You figure out what
the magazines are.

00:48:48.240 --> 00:48:49.180
You get the addresses.

00:48:49.180 --> 00:48:50.846
You send these things
out every quarter.

00:48:50.846 --> 00:48:53.260
Like it's all very
straightforward.

00:48:53.260 --> 00:48:56.360
But it turns out I have
a job that I would really

00:48:56.360 --> 00:48:57.760
rather spend my time doing.

00:48:57.760 --> 00:49:01.340
So yeah, where's the trade off?

00:49:01.340 --> 00:49:05.610
AUDIENCE: So if you were doing
another book like the coffee

00:49:05.610 --> 00:49:07.432
book, what will
you do differently?

00:49:07.432 --> 00:49:09.140
ALON HALEVY: What
would I do differently?

00:49:14.910 --> 00:49:17.990
I remain an eternal optimist.

00:49:17.990 --> 00:49:23.369
I think that if I actually
would do more marketing

00:49:23.369 --> 00:49:24.160
it would do better.

00:49:24.160 --> 00:49:25.743
The other thing I
could do is actually

00:49:25.743 --> 00:49:28.840
try to figure out what
people care about reading

00:49:28.840 --> 00:49:31.220
and tailor it more to that.

00:49:31.220 --> 00:49:34.680
The book right now
is, it's a bunch

00:49:34.680 --> 00:49:37.110
of stories about
different coffee cultures

00:49:37.110 --> 00:49:39.280
in different countries.

00:49:39.280 --> 00:49:42.110
But it wasn't possible
for me to really test out

00:49:42.110 --> 00:49:46.737
what people care about
reading in the coffee world.

00:49:46.737 --> 00:49:48.320
And people in the
coffee world itself,

00:49:48.320 --> 00:49:50.653
even though they bought a lot
of books, they don't read.

00:49:50.653 --> 00:49:52.470
They drink coffee.

00:49:52.470 --> 00:49:53.030
OK.

00:49:53.030 --> 00:49:55.990
They read tweets.

00:49:55.990 --> 00:50:01.490
But in general, I mean
books about food and drinks

00:50:01.490 --> 00:50:04.280
don't do very well, which
is part of the reason

00:50:04.280 --> 00:50:09.030
that publishers were
nice but not forthcoming.

00:50:09.030 --> 00:50:11.226
So maybe I would write
a book about big data.

00:50:11.226 --> 00:50:12.140
[INAUDIBLE]

00:50:12.140 --> 00:50:14.380
So a coffee table
book should be bigger,

00:50:14.380 --> 00:50:17.780
because most people-- yeah.

00:50:17.780 --> 00:50:20.990
If I were to do it again, I
would do a very interactive--

00:50:20.990 --> 00:50:24.640
something really out there,
like an interactive book that

00:50:24.640 --> 00:50:25.678
enables you to--

00:50:25.678 --> 00:50:27.112
AUDIENCE: Pop-up book.

00:50:27.112 --> 00:50:28.842
A pop-up book.

00:50:28.842 --> 00:50:30.300
ALON HALEVY: No,
no, like something

00:50:30.300 --> 00:50:32.450
that you can put on
your iPad and you really

00:50:32.450 --> 00:50:33.840
have an experience.

00:50:33.840 --> 00:50:36.910
That you can-- I don't know--
that'll actually help you make

00:50:36.910 --> 00:50:38.250
the coffee or--

